feat: Implement auto-hiding sidebar for mobile UX

This commit improves the user experience on mobile devices by implementing an auto-hiding sidebar.

- **CSS**: Media queries have been added to apply a new layout for the sidebar on screens with a width of 768px or less. The sidebar is now positioned absolutely and uses a `transform` to slide in and out of view.
- **JavaScript**:
    - An `isMobile()` helper function has been added to detect small screens.
    - The `loadGuide` and `flyToPoi` functions now check if the user is on a mobile device and, if so, automatically hide the sidebar after an action is completed, providing a full-screen map view.
    - The `switchSidebarView` function has been updated to handle showing the sidebar if it was previously hidden on mobile.

`294-297`: **Same as prod commit step: pin action, guard empty commits, and confirm branch protection compatibility** Mirror the hardening and checks suggested for the production “Commit Changes” step: - Pin action to a commit SHA. - Guard for no-op commits or enable allow-empty if the action supports it. - Ensure the GitHub App token can push to the dev branch under any protection rules.

`11-11`: **Confirm intent: enabling concurrent runs per branch can overlap deployments and commits** Setting cancel-in-progress: false at the workflow level allows multiple runs on the same branch to proceed concurrently. This can lead to: - Two deploys to the same environment running at once (race on remote state). - Competing “Commit Changes” steps pushing VERSION.txt (potential merge conflicts or out-of-order history). - Duplicate Sentry releases and duplicated “sync back to dev” PRs. If that’s not explicitly desired, consider scoping concurrency to deployment jobs and cancelling in-progress runs per ref. Example: ```diff -concurrency: - group: ${{ github.ref }} - cancel-in-progress: false +concurrency: + group: ${{ github.ref }} + cancel-in-progress: true ``` Or, keep top-level default but also add job-level controls just for deploy jobs: ```yaml # Under deploy-prod: concurrency: group: deploy-prod-${{ github.ref }} cancel-in-progress: true # Under deploy-dev: concurrency: group: deploy-dev-${{ github.ref }} cancel-in-progress: true ``` --- `238-242`: **Pin action to a commit SHA and verify behaviour on empty commits and branch protections** - Security: Pin dsanders11/github-app-commit-action to a commit SHA for supply-chain hardening (consistent with the SHA pinning you already use elsewhere). - Behaviour: If there are no file changes (common after reading VERSION.txt), confirm the action does not fail. If it does, guard the step with a “has changes” check or enable an allow-empty flag if supported. - Branch protection: Ensure your GitHub App is permitted to push directly to protected branches (if applicable). App tokens do not inherently bypass branch protection. Minimal hardening: ```diff -uses: dsanders11/github-app-commit-action@v1 +uses: dsanders11/github-app-commit-action@ ``` Optional guard (outside this block) to avoid running the commit step when nothing changed: ```yaml - name: Detect changes id: changes run: | if git diff --quiet; then echo "changed=false" >> "$GITHUB_OUTPUT" else echo "changed=true" >> "$GITHUB_OUTPUT" fi # Then on the commit step: if: steps.changes.outputs.changed == 'true' ``` Also note that removing previous file-pattern exclusions means workflow file changes will now be committed if present, which can retrigger this workflow. Confirm this is intended. --- `221-221`: **Typo in environment variable name: DEPLPOYER_REPO** The variable name appears misspelled as DEPLPOYER_REPO in both prod and dev deploy environments. If your deployment tooling expects DEPLOYER_REPO, this will be ignored. Proposed fix: ```diff - DEPLPOYER_REPO: ${{ vars.DEPLOYER_REPO }} + DEPLOYER_REPO: ${{ vars.DEPLOYER_REPO }} ``` Also applies to: 282-282
